@page "/integration"

<PageTitle>Custom Element Integration Guide</PageTitle>

<div class="guide">

    <div class="guide-hero">
        <div class="guide-hero-label">Blazor WebAssembly · Custom Elements</div>
        <h1>Building &amp; Integrating<br />Blazor Custom Elements</h1>
        <p>
            A step-by-step guide to turning a Blazor component into a reusable
            HTML custom element and embedding it on any website — exactly as done
            in this solution.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="guide-body">

        <!-- ─── What is it? ─── -->
        <section class="guide-section">
            <h2>What is a Blazor Custom Element?</h2>
            <p>
                The <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Web_components/Using_custom_elements"
                       target="_blank" rel="noopener">Custom Elements API</a> lets you define your own HTML tags.
                Blazor's <code>RegisterCustomElement&lt;T&gt;</code> wires a Blazor WebAssembly component to
                one of those tags. Once registered, <code>&lt;calc-ulator&gt;</code> works like a native browser
                element and can be dropped into <em>any</em> HTML page — React, Vue, plain HTML, or
                Blazor Server — without any Blazor dependency on the host side.
            </p>
            <div class="info-cards">
                <div class="info-card">
                    <div class="info-card-icon">🧩</div>
                    <div>
                        <strong>Framework-agnostic</strong>
                        <p>Use the tag in any HTML page or JavaScript framework — no Blazor SDK on the host required.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <div class="info-card-icon">⚡</div>
                    <div>
                        <strong>Runs in the browser</strong>
                        <p>Component logic executes 100% client-side via WebAssembly — no server round-trips.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <div class="info-card-icon">📦</div>
                    <div>
                        <strong>Self-contained bundle</strong>
                        <p>The WASM output includes the .NET runtime, your component, and all dependencies.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- ─── Architecture ─── -->
        <section class="guide-section">
            <h2>Architecture of This Solution</h2>
            <div class="arch-diagram">
                <div class="arch-box arch-server">
                    <div class="arch-title">CalcApp.Server</div>
                    <div class="arch-badge">Blazor Server</div>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Handles routing &amp; server-side rendering</li>
                        <li>Embeds <code>&lt;calc-ulator&gt;</code> on <code>Home.razor</code></li>
                        <li>Serves WASM files from <code>wwwroot/calculator/</code></li>
                        <li>Configures MIME types for <code>.dat</code> / <code>.wasm</code></li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="arch-arrow">→</div>
                <div class="arch-box arch-wasm">
                    <div class="arch-title">Calculator.Wasm</div>
                    <div class="arch-badge">Blazor WebAssembly</div>
                    <ul>
                        <li><code>Calculator.razor</code> component</li>
                        <li>Registered as <code>&lt;calc-ulator&gt;</code></li>
                        <li>Published via MSBuild into Server's <code>wwwroot</code></li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- ─── Steps ─── -->
        <section class="guide-section">
            <h2>Step by Step</h2>

            <!-- Step 1 -->
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-num">1</div>
                <div class="step-body">
                    <h3>Create a Blazor WebAssembly standalone project</h3>
                    <p>Create a regular Blazor WASM project. This becomes the component library. The
                       <code>Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.CustomElements</code> package is included
                       by default from .NET 7 onwards.</p>
                    <pre class="code-block"><code>dotnet new blazorwasm -n Calculator.Wasm --no-https</code></pre>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Step 2 -->
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-num">2</div>
                <div class="step-body">
                    <h3>Register the component as a custom element</h3>
                    <p>In <code>Program.cs</code> of the WASM project, use
                       <code>RegisterCustomElement</code> instead of the standard root component
                       registration. Pass the HTML tag name you want the component to respond to:</p>
                    <pre class="code-block"><code>// Program.cs (Calculator.Wasm)
var builder = WebAssemblyHostBuilder.CreateDefault(args);

// Remove this:
//   builder.RootComponents.Add&lt;App&gt;("#app");

// Add this instead:
builder.RootComponents
       .RegisterCustomElement&lt;Calculator&gt;("calc-ulator");

await builder.Build().RunAsync();</code></pre>
                    <div class="guide-note">
                        Custom element names <strong>must contain a hyphen</strong> (e.g.
                        <code>calc-ulator</code>, not <code>calculator</code>). This is enforced
                        by the browser to distinguish custom elements from native HTML elements.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Step 3 -->
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-num">3</div>
                <div class="step-body">
                    <h3>Publish and copy the WASM bundle into the host project</h3>
                    <p>Add an MSBuild target to the host's <code>.csproj</code> that publishes
                       Calculator.Wasm and copies its output to <code>wwwroot/calculator/</code>.
                       Key decisions made in this solution:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <strong>Always publish in Release mode.</strong> Debug builds include
                            <code>Microsoft.DotNet.HotReload.WebAssembly.Browser</code> with a
                            fingerprinted filename that the WASM bootstrap cannot locate without a
                            matching import map entry.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong>Exclude <code>.br</code> / <code>.gz</code> variants.</strong>
                            The host's <code>MapStaticAssets()</code> discovers pre-compressed
                            siblings and serves them via content negotiation. Because our copied
                            files differ in file metadata from the originals, the middleware can
                            pair the wrong file with the wrong encoding, causing
                            <code>ERR_CONTENT_DECODING_FAILED</code> in the browser.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong>Clean the publish output directory first.</strong> Without a
                            clean, stale fingerprinted files (e.g. <code>dotnet.OLDHASH.js</code>
                            from a previous SDK version) accumulate alongside the new ones. MSBuild's
                            Copy task then fails because its 1-to-1 DestinationFiles mapping sees
                            multiple source files.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong>Create stable-name copies of fingerprinted JS files.</strong>
                            <code>blazor.webassembly.js</code> internally does dynamic
                            <code>import('./dotnet.js')</code> calls using stable (non-fingerprinted)
                            names. The WASM project's own <code>index.html</code> provides an
                            <code>&lt;importmap&gt;</code> to resolve these — but a host page cannot
                            have a second import map. The workaround is to copy
                            <code>dotnet.HASH.js → dotnet.js</code> etc. so the browser can resolve
                            the imports directly without a map.
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <pre class="code-block"><code>&lt;!-- In CalcApp.Server.csproj --&gt;
&lt;Target Name="PublishCalculatorWasm" BeforeTargets="Build"
        Inputs="..\Calculator.Wasm\Calculator.Wasm.csproj;..."
        Outputs="wwwroot\calculator\_framework\blazor.webassembly.js"&gt;

  &lt;!-- 1. Clean stale output to prevent fingerprint accumulation --&gt;
  &lt;RemoveDir Directories="obj\wasm-publish" /&gt;

  &lt;!-- 2. Publish in Release mode --&gt;
  &lt;Exec Command="dotnet publish ..\Calculator.Wasm\Calculator.Wasm.csproj
      -c Release -o obj\wasm-publish --nologo -v quiet" /&gt;

  &lt;!-- 3. Collect files, excluding pre-compressed variants --&gt;
  &lt;ItemGroup&gt;
    &lt;WasmFiles Include="obj\wasm-publish\wwwroot\**\*"
               Exclude="obj\wasm-publish\wwwroot\**\*.br;
                        obj\wasm-publish\wwwroot\**\*.gz" /&gt;
  &lt;/ItemGroup&gt;

  &lt;!-- 4. Copy to wwwroot/calculator/ --&gt;
  &lt;Copy SourceFiles="@@(WasmFiles)"
        DestinationFiles="@@(WasmFiles-&gt;
          'wwwroot\calculator\%(RecursiveDir)%(Filename)%(Extension)')"
        OverwriteReadOnlyFiles="true" /&gt;

  &lt;!-- 5. Create stable-name copies of fingerprinted JS files --&gt;
  &lt;Copy SourceFiles="@@(FingerprintedDotnetCoreJs)"
        DestinationFiles="wwwroot\calculator\_framework\dotnet.js" /&gt;
  &lt;Copy SourceFiles="@@(FingerprintedDotnetNativeJs)"
        DestinationFiles="wwwroot\calculator\_framework\dotnet.native.js" /&gt;
  &lt;Copy SourceFiles="@@(FingerprintedDotnetRuntimeJs)"
        DestinationFiles="wwwroot\calculator\_framework\dotnet.runtime.js" /&gt;
  &lt;Copy SourceFiles="@@(FingerprintedBlazorJs)"
        DestinationFiles="wwwroot\calculator\_framework\blazor.webassembly.js" /&gt;

&lt;/Target&gt;</code></pre>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Step 4 -->
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-num">4</div>
                <div class="step-body">
                    <h3>Configure static file MIME types in the host</h3>
                    <p>
                        ASP.NET Core's static file middleware returns <strong>404</strong> for
                        file types it doesn't recognize — even if the file exists. The WASM runtime
                        fetches <code>.dat</code> files (ICU globalization data) and <code>.wasm</code>
                        files (.NET assemblies). Register MIME type mappings before
                        <code>UseStaticFiles</code>:
                    </p>
                    <pre class="code-block"><code>// Program.cs (CalcApp.Server)
var provider = new FileExtensionContentTypeProvider();
provider.Mappings[".dat"]  = "application/octet-stream"; // ICU data
provider.Mappings[".wasm"] = "application/wasm";         // .NET assemblies
provider.Mappings[".blat"] = "application/octet-stream"; // lazy-load table

app.UseStaticFiles(new StaticFileOptions
{
    ContentTypeProvider = provider
});</code></pre>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Step 5 -->
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-num">5</div>
                <div class="step-body">
                    <h3>Load the WASM runtime and scoped CSS in the host page</h3>
                    <p>Add two tags to the host's layout (<code>App.razor</code> or
                       <code>_Layout.cshtml</code>). The stylesheet must come before the script:</p>
                    <pre class="code-block"><code>&lt;!-- Blazor scoped CSS for Calculator.Wasm components --&gt;
&lt;link rel="stylesheet" href="calculator/Calculator.Wasm.styles.css" /&gt;

&lt;!-- Bootstrap the Blazor WASM runtime (stable-name copy) --&gt;
&lt;script src="calculator/_framework/blazor.webassembly.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</code></pre>
                    <div class="guide-note">
                        The <code>styles.css</code> link is easy to overlook. Without it, all
                        <strong>Blazor-scoped CSS</strong> (the styles defined in
                        <code>Calculator.razor.css</code>) is silently ignored and the component
                        renders without any of its intended styles.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Step 6 -->
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-num">6</div>
                <div class="step-body">
                    <h3>Use the custom element on any page</h3>
                    <p>
                        Once the script is loaded the WASM runtime starts (once, regardless of
                        how many instances are on the page) and hydrates every
                        <code>&lt;calc-ulator&gt;</code> it finds in the DOM:
                    </p>
                    <pre class="code-block"><code>&lt;!-- Razor, HTML, React JSX, Vue template — anywhere --&gt;
&lt;calc-ulator&gt;&lt;/calc-ulator&gt;</code></pre>
                    <p>
                        Multiple instances on the same page are fully supported. Each runs its
                        own independent Blazor component instance.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- ─── Gotchas ─── -->
        <section class="guide-section">
            <h2>Important Gotchas</h2>

            <div class="gotchas">
                <div class="gotcha">
                    <div class="gotcha-title">Custom elements are inline by default</div>
                    <p>
                        Unknown HTML elements default to <code>display: inline</code>. This prevents
                        fixed widths and CSS grid layouts inside the component from working correctly.
                        Add one rule to your global stylesheet:
                    </p>
                    <pre class="code-block"><code>calc-ulator { display: block; }</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="gotcha">
                    <div class="gotcha-title">The host page's &lt;base href&gt; controls all asset URLs</div>
                    <p>
                        The WASM runtime resolves framework files, ICU data, and .NET assemblies
                        relative to <code>document.baseURI</code> — <em>not</em> relative to the
                        script's own URL. Keep <code>&lt;base href="/"&gt;</code> on the host page and
                        ensure all WASM files are reachable from the root path.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Do <strong>not</strong> point <code>&lt;base href&gt;</code> at
                        <code>/calculator/</code> — that would break the host app's own routing.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div class="gotcha">
                    <div class="gotcha-title">_content/ assets must also live at the document root</div>
                    <p>
                        If the WASM component depends on a Razor Class Library (which publishes
                        static assets to <code>_content/LibraryName/</code>), the WASM runtime
                        requests them relative to the document base URL — so
                        <code>/_content/MyLib/file.js</code>, not
                        <code>/calculator/_content/MyLib/file.js</code>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The MSBuild target in this solution handles this by copying the WASM
                        project's <code>_content/</code> folder into the host's
                        <code>wwwroot/_content/</code>.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div class="gotcha">
                    <div class="gotcha-title">A host page cannot have two import maps</div>
                    <p>
                        Blazor's boot script uses <code>import('./dotnet.js')</code> with stable
                        (non-fingerprinted) names. The WASM project's own <code>index.html</code>
                        provides an <code>&lt;script type="importmap"&gt;</code> to map these to the
                        fingerprinted filenames — but a browser only accepts <em>one</em> import map
                        per page, and the host app already has one.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Workaround used here: create stable-name copies of the fingerprinted files
                        (<code>dotnet.HASH.js → dotnet.js</code>) so the import resolves directly
                        without any map entry.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div class="gotcha">
                    <div class="gotcha-title">Don't copy pre-compressed (.br / .gz) files to wwwroot</div>
                    <p>
                        <code>MapStaticAssets()</code> auto-discovers <code>.br</code> and
                        <code>.gz</code> siblings in <code>wwwroot/</code> and serves them via HTTP
                        content negotiation. If the copied variants have different metadata than
                        what <code>MapStaticAssets</code> expects, it can serve the wrong compressed
                        file for a given content file, resulting in
                        <code>ERR_CONTENT_DECODING_FAILED</code>.
                        Copy only the uncompressed files; let the server compress on the fly if needed.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

    </div>
</div>
